"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-caeleb-dressel-katie-ledecky-swimming-battle-against-time\", \"text\": \"Heading into big meets, swimmers notoriously lie to themselves. The internal dialogue says that a lifetime-best performance is coming, that their training has led them to the point where they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll inevitably see a number flash on the scoreboard next to their names that they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve never produced before.\\u00c2  It isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t always a lie, of course. But it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s never always true, and the lies can become more brazen as swimmers get older. Believing that a new level of greatness is always within reach is a powerful drug.  Which is why Caeleb Dressel startled a room full of reporters with an honest admission Saturday night at the U.S. Olympic Trials in Indianapolis.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t know if I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll ever go a best time ever again,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Dressel said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThat\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s hard to say out loud.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Compare and contrast that with the words three years ago from another all-time great who is, like Dressel, 27 years old.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m always striving to be better than I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve ever been, and it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not easy when your times are world records,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Katie Ledecky said during the Tokyo Olympics. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m really tough on myself. But that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the attitude I have\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094I literally approach each race with a belief that I can swim a best time, and that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s pretty darned tough. But that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s why I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve been so successful over the years, because I approach every single race with the attitude that anything can happen, and I can break world records this race. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m going to step up and throw down. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a real blessing and a curse to have that attitude.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Both are legends in the sport who are chasing their own greatness, trying to catch up to times that were achieved at younger ages. Realistic or futile, that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s always the goal.  After a very successful meet here, winning two events and making an Olympic relay in a third, Dressel is closer to his younger self. He\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s trying to dial back to the prime years of 2019\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009321, when he was breaking world and American records.\\u00c2  His winning time in the 100 butterfly Saturday was only .32 off what he did in Omaha three years ago at Trials, and it vaults him near the top of the crowded world rankings in that event heading into Paris. In the 50 free, Dressel\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 21.41 is .37 off his 2021 Trials time and fourth in the world. His 100 freestyle time that landed him in third was about half a second off his American record, but more significantly it was behind two other American young guns\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094Jack Alexy and Chris Guiliano\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094who claimed the individual spots in that event and relegated Dressel to the relay.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI am happy with a lot of my swims, and to be back to a place that I wanted to be with the sport is exceptional,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m really proud of myself for that. So I do not know if I have one swim in particular, but getting that weight off my shoulders for 100 free, making the team, it made the rest of the week a little easier and bittersweet, because I got third. But with Jack and Chris, I mean, they deserve that spot. I got beat.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Ledecky also had a successful meet, winning four events and extending her unprecedented dominance in distance freestyle events. While her excellence should never be taken for granted, her times at Lucas Oil Stadium weren\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t dazzling. And they got comparatively slower as the meet went along.  She started with a 3:58.35 in the 400 freestyle, which was three seconds faster than she was at Olympic Trials in 2021 and only two seconds off her American record from 2016. Next up was the 200 free, which she won comfortably but did not break 1:55 and has not broken 1:54 since the Rio de Janeiro Olympics in \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009916. In the 1,500, Ledecky destroyed the field as usual but wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t thrilled with her time of 15:37.35, which was faster than the 2021 Trials but 17 seconds off the world record she set in this same city six years ago. In the 800 Saturday, Ledecky again won easily with a time that was slightly faster than the 2021 Trials.  With her best times in those events dating to a range from 2016-18, chances of turning back the clock that far seem daunting. But that doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t mean she isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t still fast enough to win races at the Olympics. And the same goes for Dressel, although his competition is closer to him in every event than some of Ledecky\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s is (specifically the 1,500 and 800).  This is the burden of aging. Time is undefeated, which makes the belief in turning back the clock\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094literally and figuratively\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094more difficult.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWhen you are 19, 20, 21, you keep chipping away, chipping away, chipping away,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Dressel said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI am still working harder than ever, finding outlets, finding every path I can take to shave those couple tenths. I do not know. I do not know if I can do that. I am really good at racing. You put me in a race, I will make it close, as close as I possibly can, even if I have to try to kill myself to get there. I will put myself in those situations.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Caeleb Dressel has put himself in Paris in multiple events as a three-time Olympian. Ledecky has multiple events and is heading to her fourth Summer Games. They have stood the test of time, even if they are still chasing their old times.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2025ABG-SI LLC- SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"